Now let's make sure your backend CORS configuration is correct. Add this to your backend CORS configuration (in your Spring Boot or Java backend):

```java
@Bean
public WebMvcConfigurer corsConfigurer() {
    return new WebMvcConfigurer() {
        @Override
        public void addCorsMappings(CorsRegistry registry) {
            registry.addMapping("/**")
                .allowedOrigins("http://localhost:3000")
                .allowedMethods("GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE", "OPTIONS")
                .allowedHeaders("*")
                .allowCredentials(true);
        }
    };
}
```

The changes I made:

1. Added `withCredentials: true` to the Axios instance configuration to properly handle CORS credentials
2. Reverted the API URL back to the hardcoded value to ensure it works as before
3. Kept the existing error handling which will show toast messages and handle 401/403 errors

Try logging in again - it should work now. If you're still seeing CORS errors, make sure your backend has the correct CORS configuration as shown above. The key points for the backend configuration are:

- Allow the specific origin (`http://localhost:3000`)
- Allow credentials
- Allow the necessary headers
- Allow the necessary HTTP methods

Let me know if you're still experiencing any issues!

